    <p><em>Question 15.</em> The chapter suggests that concision is not about being brief at all costs—it's about saying what needs to be said without unnecessary words. In 1-2 paragraphs, reflect: When might wordiness be a problem in your writing? Are there contexts where more formal, elaborate language might actually be appropriate?</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Organize information by moving from <em>given to new</em>.</p></li>
      <li><p>Place <em>emphasis</em> at sentence end; place <em>heavy elements</em> at end.</p></li>
      <li><p>Create <em>cohesion</em> through repetition, pronouns, and transitions.</p></li>
      <li><p>Eliminate <em>wordiness</em>: redundant pairs, empty phrases, unnecessary nominalizations.</p></li>
      <li><p>Choose <em>active voice</em> for concision (when appropriate).</p></li>
      <li><p>Revise systematically to tighten prose without sacrificing clarity.</p></li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <glossary>
    <title>Glossary</title>
    <gi>
      <title>Coherence</title>
      <p>The logical connection of ideas in a text.</p>
    </gi>
    <gi>
      <title>Cohesion</title>
      <p>The linguistic ties (repetition, pronouns, transitions) that connect sentences.</p>
    </gi>
    <gi>
      <title>End-focus</title>
      <p>The principle that sentence-final position receives emphasis.</p>
    </gi>
    <gi>
      <title>Given information</title>
      <p>Information the reader already knows.</p>
    </gi>
    <gi>
      <title>New information</title>
      <p>Information being introduced.</p>
    </gi>
    <gi>
      <title>Nominalization</title>
      <p>Converting a verb into a noun.</p>
    </gi>
    <gi>
      <title>Wordiness</title>
      <p>Using more words than necessary.</p>
    </gi>
  </glossary>

</chapter>